\section{Portfolio Website Structure}

\subsection{Overview of Sections}

The portfolio is a page application built entirely in HTML and CSS, that I coded using VS code. It is organised into five main sections, with each section designed to present different parts of my profile to potential employers in a clear and professional way

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Hero / Home}: An introduction featuring my name, BSc Software Engineering title, a short personal description, key achievements (2+ years of experience, 5+ completed projects, and fluency in four languages), along with buttons to download my CV or contact me.
  \item \textbf{Skills \& Services}: A responsive three-column layout highlighting six key skills: Software Development, Data \& Analytics, Event Management, Leadership, Problem Solving, and Multilingual Communication.
  \item \textbf{About Me}: A two-column layout containing a short biography, my personal philosophy, and a "Day in My Life" bar chart showing how I balance studying, social activities, sports, and rest.
  \item \textbf{Experience \& Projects}: A vertical timeline presenting my current BSc studies at Gisma University of Applied Sciences, my experience organising gaming tournaments at the American School of Antananarivo, and previous work experience at Camelia and Simba Supermarket in Kigali, Rwanda.
  \item \textbf{Contact}: Contact information, interests, and a message form allowing potential employers or collaborators to reach out directly.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Navigation}

A fixed top navigation bar provides a smooth scroll that links to each section. JavaScript is used to highlight the currently active section link as the user scrolls. A ``Hire Me'' call-to-action button in the nav anchors directly to the Contact section, optimising the user journey for a potential employer.

\subsection{GitHub Repository Structure}

The project is organised into two separate repositories, each serving a different purpose.

The first repository contains the PDF version of my curriculum vitae (CV). This document includes my personal information, educational background, technical skills, work experience, projects, certifications, and contact details. It acts as the primary professional document that can be downloaded and shared with potential employers.

The second repository contains the complete source code for my personal portfolio website. All website files, including the HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, and other supporting assets, are stored within the repository's Codespace, making the project easy to access, edit, maintain, and deploy at any time.

\section{Design Decisions}

\subsection{Visual Language}

The website adopts a \textbf{dark brutalist typographic aesthetic}. This was a my  choice to stand out from generic, template heavy portfolios common among students and they also be lookign all similar in most cases. The design system is defined by a small set of CSS custom properties (variables):

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Background:} Near black (\texttt{\#111111}) with layered dark panels (\texttt{\#1a1a1a}, \texttt{\#222222}).
  \item \textbf{Accent colour:} Burnt orange (\texttt{\#E8622A}), used for headings, icons, interactive hover states, and highlighted statistics. Orange was chosen for its energy and visibility against dark backgrounds, signalling confidence and creativity.
  \item \textbf{Text:} Off white (\texttt{\#f5f5f0}) for primary content; muted grey (\texttt{\#888880}) for secondary text, creating clear hierarchy without harsh contrast.
  \item \textbf{Borders:} Subtle semi transparent white (\texttt{rgba(255,255,255,0.08)}) to create depth without visual noise.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Typography}

Two Google Fonts are used:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Unbounded} (weights 400, 700, 900) for all headings, section labels, and logotype. Its wide, geometric letterforms reinforce the bold aesthetic.
  \item \textbf{DM Sans} (weights 300, 400, 500) for body copy and UI text. A humanist sans serif that ensures readability at small sizes.
\end{itemize}

This combination creates a balance between a modern, attractive appearance and easy readability. It was chosen intentionally to make the portfolio visually appealing while ensuring that employers can quickly and comfortably read the content, helping to create a strong first impression.


\subsection{Layout}

The website uses CSS Grid to organise its main sections, including the hero, skills, about, experience, and contact areas. This layout provides a clean and well structured design while making it easy to arrange content consistently across the page. On smaller screens, the grid automatically adjusts to a single column layout, ensuring the website remains fully responsive and user friendly on tablets and mobile devices.

Using CSS Grid instead of JavaScript layout libraries improves the website's performance by reducing unnecessary scripts. This results in faster loading times, smoother navigation, and code that is simpler to read, maintain, and update.

The navigation bar uses position: fixed, allowing it to remain visible at the top of the page while users scroll through the website. To improve readability and give the interface a modern appearance, a backdrop filter: blur(12px) effect is applied, creating a glass like background that keeps the navigation clear over different page sections without blocking the content underneath. This enhances both the visual design and the overall user experience.

\subsection{Interactivity}

The website includes a small amount of interactivity to improve the user The website includes a small amount of interactivity to improve the user experience without making the interface overly complex. Features such as smooth scrolling allow users to move easily between sections, while a subtle card hover effect provides visual feedback when users interact with different content cards. In addition, a lightweight JavaScript scroll listener automatically highlights the active navigation link, helping users see which section of the website they are currently viewing.

No large JavaScript frameworks or external libraries were used during development. Instead, the website was built using HTML, CSS, and vanilla JavaScript, demonstrating a strong understanding of core web development principles while keeping the website lightweight, fast, and easy to maintain.

