\subsection{LaTeX CV}

The CV was prepared in Overleaf using the \textbf{AltaCV} template, customised with a navy and steel blue colour scheme. It includes all relevant personal, academic, and professional information sourced from my actual background: education at Gisma and the American School of Antananarivo, work experience at Camelia and Simba Supermarket, skills, languages, and interests. The compiled PDF is exported and committed to the GitHub repository, making it directly downloadable from the portfolio.

\section{Content}

The content of the portfolio was chosen to represent the most relevant aspects of my profile for a working student or junior software engineering role.

\textbf{Academic projects}: The Projects section highlights two practical software development projects completed as part of my coursework. The first is a Python Library Management System, which was developed using object oriented programming principles and validated with a comprehensive 69 test suite, demonstrating the reliability and quality of the code. The second is a MySQL Hotel Reservation System, which includes a well designed relational database and an Entity Relationship (ER) diagram to illustrate the database structure and relationships.

\textbf{Transferable skills}: Event management and leadership, showed by the gaming tournament and the Sports Council vice presidency, are included because they speak to soft skills that employers value alongside technical ability.

\textbf{Languages}: Kinyarwanda (native), French (fluent), English (fluent), Spanish (conversational), and German (beginner) are listed with a dot scale visual. Being multilingual is a genuine differentiator in Berlin's international tech market.

\textbf{Personal philosophy and ``Day in My Life''}: These elements were included to give the portfolio a human dimension and allow a hiring manager to assess cultural fit, not only technical competence.

\section{Strengths and Weaknesses}

\subsection{Strengths}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Distinctive visual identity.} The dark brutalist aesthetic is immediately memorable compared to generic Bootstrap or Wix portfolios, which matters in competitive hiring contexts.
  \item \textbf{Zero dependency implementation.} The entire site is a single HTML file with no build tools, no frameworks, and no backend. This makes it trivially deployable, fast loading, and easy to maintain.
  \item \textbf{Responsive typography and spacing.} Although a formal media-query breakpoint system was not implemented, the fluid grid and relative units make the layout tolerable across a range of screen sizes.
  \item \textbf{Integrated CV download.} Providing direct access to the LaTeX-compiled PDF from the hero section reduces friction for a recruiter reviewing the portfolio.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Weaknesses}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Limited mobile responsiveness.}: One limitation of the current website is that the two column layouts used in the hero, about, and contact sections do not adapt perfectly on screens smaller than 768 px. Although the website remains usable, the content can appear cramped or uneven on smaller mobile devices. In a future version, the layout will be adjusted so these sections rearrange more smoothly into a single column format on narrow screens. This improvement will provide a better viewing experience, improve readability, and ensure the website is fully responsive across a wider range of screen sizes and devices.
  \item \textbf{No live project demos.} While projects are described in the experience section, there are no embedded demos, GitHub links per project, or screenshots. Adding these would make the technical claims verifiable to a hiring manager.
  \item \textbf{Static contact form.} The message form has no backend handler; submissions are not delivered. Connecting it to a service such as Formspree or Netlify Forms would make it functional without requiring a server.
  \item \textbf{Accessibility.} Another limitation is that the colour contrast between some muted grey text and the dark background may not always provide the best readability for all users. In some areas, the contrast may not fully meet WCAG AA accessibility guidelines, making the content harder to read for users with visual impairments. In a future version, the colour scheme will be reviewed and adjusted to improve text contrast, making the website more accessible, easier to read, and compliant with recognised web accessibility standards.
\end{itemize}

\section{Future Improvements}

Given more time, the following additions would significantly improve the portfolio:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Projects section with live links}: A dedicated section showcasing GitHub repositories with descriptions, technologies used, and links to deployed demos or code.
  \item \textbf{Blog / writing section}: Documenting learning (coursework insights, tutorials, technical reflections) would demonstrate intellectual curiosity and improve SEO.
  \item \textbf{Full mobile responsiveness}: A mobile-first redesign with tested breakpoints at 480px, 768px, and 1024px.
  \item \textbf{Dark/light mode toggle}: A JavaScript-powered theme switch to increase accessibility and demonstrate DOM manipulation skills.
  \item \textbf{Automated CI/CD}: A GitHub Actions workflow to validate HTML, run Lighthouse audits on every push, and auto-deploy to GitHub Pages on merge.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}

This portfolio was created to show both my technical skills and who I am in a clear, practical, and visually interesting way. Every major design choice was made for a reason. For example, I used a dark colour scheme to make the site easier to read and give it a modern look, and I kept JavaScript to a minimum so the website loads quickly and is easier to maintain. The GitHub repository is well organised, includes clear documentation, and uses version control to record the development process from start to finish.

There are still areas that can be improved. The website is not fully responsive on all mobile devices, and the projects section could include more detailed or advanced work. Recognising these weaknesses has helped me identify clear goals for future updates. Overall, the portfolio meets the requirements of the assignment by providing a deployed GitHub Pages website, a professionally formatted LaTeX CV, an explanation of the design decisions, and an honest evaluation of its strengths and areas for improvement.

